<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Arctostaphylos hooveri </i>is a long-lived, evergreen, sclerophyllous shrub that grows up to 8 m. Plants lack a lignotuber. Leaves are glaucous, broadly oblong to ovate, and sometimes with irregularly toothed margins. Seeds collect in a seed bank as stones. Seedling mortality is high in areas with annuals and with drought. Stands occur mainly on shale in the Monterey Bay District of Los Padres National Forest (Borchert et al. 2004). It is also extensive at the University of California’s Landels-Hill Big Creek Reserve in the Gamboa Point area. <i>A. hooveri </i>is a CNPS list 4 species. Stands occur on upper ridges typically above the summer inversion zone (the upper average limit of fog), but still are ameliorated by cool maritime air. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
